nn 3_13_the_chain_rule
ln The Chain Rule.
ln Suppose $y = f(u)$ is differentiable at $u = g(x)$ and $u = g(x)$
ln is differentiable at $x$. The composite function $f(g(x))$ is
ln differentiable at $x$, and its derivative can be expressed
ln in two equivalent ways.
ln 
ln $$\
ln {dy \over dx} = {dy \over du} \cdot {du \over dx}
ln $$
ln 
ln $$\
ln {d \over dx}(f(g(x))) = f'(g(x)) \cdot g'(x)
ln $$
ff The Chain Rule
fb Suppose \(y = f(u)\) is differentiable at \(u = g(x)\) and \(u = g(x)\)
fb is differentiable at \(x\). The composite function \(f(g(x))\) is
fb differentiable at \(x\), and its derivative can be expressed
fb in two equivalent ways.
fb 
fb \(
fb {dy \over dx} = {dy \over du} \cdot {du \over dx}
fb \)
fb 
fb \(
fb {d \over dx}(f(g(x))) = f'(g(x)) \cdot g'(x)
fb \)

nn 3_14_chain_rule_for_powers
ln Chain Rule for Powers.
ln If $g$ is differentiable for all $x$ in its domain and $p$
ln is a real number, then
ln 
ln $$\
ln {d \over dx} \big((g(x))^p\big) = p(g(x))^{p - 1}g'(x)
ln $$
ff Chain Rule for Powers
fb If \(g\) is differentiable for all \(x\) in its domain and \(p\)
fb is a real number, then
fb 
fb \(
fb {d \over dx} \big((g(x))^p\big) = p(g(x))^{p - 1}g'(x)
fb \)

nn 3_15_derivative_of_ln_x
ln Derivative of $\ln x$.
ln $$\
ln {d \over dx} (\ln x) = {1 \over x}, \hbox{for} \, x > 0
ln $$
ln 
ln $$\
ln {d \over dx} (\ln |x|) = {1 \over x}, \hbox{for} \, x \ne 0
ln $$
ln 
ln If $u$ is differentiable at $x$ and $u(x) \ne 0$, then
ln 
ln $$\
ln {d \over dx} (\ln |u(x)|) = {
ln u'(x) \over u(x)
ln }
ln $$
ff Derivative of $\ln x$
fb \(
fb {d \over dx} (\ln x) = {1 \over x}, \hbox{for} \, x > 0
fb \)
fb 
fb \(
fb {d \over dx} (\ln |x|) = {1 \over x}, \hbox{for} \, x \ne 0
fb \)
fb 
fb If \(u\) is differentiable at \(x\) and \(u(x) \ne 0\), then
fb 
fb \(
fb {d \over dx} (\ln |u(x)|) = {
fb u'(x) \over u(x)
fb }
fb \)

nn 3_16_theorem_of_bx
ln Theorem of $b^x$.
ln If $b > 0$ and $b \ne 1$, then for all $x$,
ln 
ln $$\
ln {d \over dx}(b^x) = b^x \ln b
ln $$
ff Theorem of $b^x$
fb If \(b > 0\) and \(b \ne 1\), then for all \(x\),
fb 
fb \(
fb {d \over dx}(b^x) = b^x \ln b
fb \)

nn 3_17_general_power_rule
ln General Power Rule.
ln For real numbers $p$ and for $x > 0$,
ln $$\
ln {d \over dx}(x^p) = px^{p - 1}.
ln $$
ln 
ln Furthermore, if $u$ is a positive differentiable function
ln on its domain, then
ln 
ln $$\
ln {d \over dx} (u(x)^p) = p(u(x))^{p - 1} \cdot u'(x)
ln $$
ff General Power Rule
fb For real numbers \(p\) and for \(x > 0\),
fb \(
fb {d \over dx}(x^p) = px^{p - 1}.
fb \)
fb 
fb Furthermore, if \(u\) is a positive differentiable function
fb on its domain, then
fb 
fb \(
fb {d \over dx} (u(x)^p) = p(u(x))^{p - 1} \cdot u'(x)
fb \)

nn 3_18_derivative_of_logbx
ln Derivative of $\log_{b}x$.
ln If $b > 0$ and $b \ne 1$, then
ln $$\
ln {d \over dx} (log_{b} x) = {1 \over {x \ln b}}, \hbox{for}
ln \, x > 0
ln $$
ln 
ln and
ln 
ln $$\
ln {d \over dx}(log_{b}|x|) = {1 \over {x \ln b}}, \hbox{for}
ln \, x \ne 0
ln $$
ln 
ff Derivative of $\log_{b}x$
