nn 3_21_derivative_of_the_inverse_function
ln Derivative of the Inverse Function.
ln Let $f$ be differentiable and have an invese on an interval $I$.
ln If $x_0$ is a point of $I$ at which $f'(x_0) \ne 0$, then $f^{-1}$
ln is differentiable at $y_0 = f(x_0)$ and
ln 
ln $$\
ln (f^{-1})'(y_0) = {1 \over f'(x_0)},
ln \, \hbox{where} \, y_0 = f(x_0).
ln $$
ff Derivative of the Inverse Function
fb Let \(f\) be differentiable and have an invese on an interval \(I\).
fb If \(x_0\) is a point of \(I\) at which \(f'(x_0) \ne 0\), then \(f^{-1}\)
fb is differentiable at \(y_0 = f(x_0)\) and
fb 
fb \(
fb (f^{-1})'(y_0) = {1 \over f'(x_0)},
fb \, \hbox{where} \, y_0 = f(x_0).
fb \)

nn 4_1_extreme_value_theorem
ln Extreme Value Theorem.
ln A function that is continuous on a cl,soed interval $[a, b]$
ln has an absolute maximum value and an absolute minimum value on
ln that interval.
ff Extreme Value Theorem
fb A function that is continuous on a cl,soed interval \([a, b]\)
fb has an absolute maximum value and an absolute minimum value on
fb that interval.

nn 4_2_local_extreme_value_theorem
ln Local Extreme Value Theorem.
ln If $f$ has a local maximum or minimum value at $c$ and
ln $f'(c)$ exists, then $f'(c) = 0$.
ff Local Extreme Value Theorem
fb If \(f\) has a local maximum or minimum value at \(c\) and
fb \(f'(c)\) exists, then \(f'(c) = 0\).

nn 4_3_rolles_theorem
ln Rolle's Theorem.
ln Let $f$ be continuous on a clsoed interval $[a,b]$ and differentiable on $(a, b)$
ln with $f(a) = f(b)$. There is at least one point $c$ in $(a, b)$ such that
ln $f'(c) = 0$.
ff Rolle's Theorem
fb Let \(f\) be continuous on a clsoed interval \([a,b]\) and differentiable on \((a, b)\)
fb with \(f(a) = f(b)\). There is at least one point \(c\) in \((a, b)\) such that
fb \(f'(c) = 0\).

nn 4_4_mean_value_theorem
ln Mean Value Theorem.
ln If $f$ is continuous on the closed interval $[a,b]$ and differentiable
ln on $(a, b)$, then there is at least one point $c$ in $(a, b)$
ln such that
ln $$\
ln {f(b) - f(a) \over b - a} = f'(c)
ln $$
ff Mean Value Theorem
fb If \(f\) is continuous on the closed interval \([a,b]\) and differentiable
fb on \((a, b)\), then there is at least one point \(c\) in \((a, b)\)
fb such that
fb \(
fb {f(b) - f(a) \over b - a} = f'(c)
fb \)

nn 4_5_zero_derivative_implies_constant
ln Zero Derivative Implies Constant Function.
ln If $f$ is differentiable and $f'(x) = 0$ at all points of an
ln open interval $I$, then $f$ is a constant function on $I$.
ff Zero Derivative Implies Constant Function
fb If \(f\) is differentiable and \(f'(x) = 0\) at all points of an
fb open interval \(I\), then \(f\) is a constant function on \(I\).

nn 4_6_functions_with_equal_derivatives
ln Functions with Equal Derivatives Differ by a Constant.
ln If two functinos of the property that $f'(x) = g'(x)$, for
ln all $x$ of an open interval $I$, then $f(x) - g(x) = C$ on $I$,
ln where $C$ is a constant; that is, $f$ and $g$ differ by a constant.
ff Functions with Equal Derivatives Differ by a Constant
fb If two functinos of the property that \(f'(x) = g'(x)\), for
fb all \(x\) of an open interval \(I\), then \(f(x) - g(x) = C\) on \(I\),
fb where \(C\) is a constant; that is, \(f\) and \(g\) differ by a constant.

nn 4_7_test_for_intervals_of_increase
ln Test for Intervals of Increase and Decrease.
ln Suppose $f$ is continuous on an interval $I$ and differentiable
ln at all interior points of $I$. If $f'(x) > 0$ at all interior
ln points of $I$, then $f$ is increasing on $I$. If $f'(x) < 0$
ln at all interior points of $I$, then $f$ is decreasing on $I$.
ff Test for Intervals of Increase and Decrease
fb Suppose \(f\) is continuous on an interval \(I\) and differentiable
fb at all interior points of \(I\). If \(f'(x) > 0\) at all interior
fb points of \(I\), then \(f\) is increasing on \(I\). If \(f'(x) < 0\)
fb at all interior points of \(I\), then \(f\) is decreasing on \(I\).

nn 4_8_first_derivative_test
ln First Derivative Test.
ln Assume $f$ is continuous on an interval that contains a critical
ln point $c$, and assume $f$ is differentiable on an interval containing
ln $c$, except perhaps at $c$ itself.
ln \par
ln If $f'$ changes sign from positive to negative as $x$ increases
ln through $c$, then $f$ has a {\bf local maximum} at $c$.
ln \par
ln If $f'$ changes sign from netagive to positive as $x$ increases
ln through $c$, then $f$ has a {\bf local minimum} at $c$.
ln \par
ln If $f'$ is positive on both sides near $c$ or negative on boths
ln sides near $c$, then $f$ has no local extreme value at $c$.
ff First Derivative Test
fb Assume \(f\) is continuous on an interval that contains a critical
fb point \(c\), and assume \(f\) is differentiable on an interval containing
fb \(c\), except perhaps at \(c\) itself.
fb <br><br>
fb If \(f'\) changes sign from positive to negative as \(x\) increases
fb through \(c\), then \(f\) has a {\bf local maximum} at \(c\).
fb <br><br>
fb If \(f'\) changes sign from netagive to positive as \(x\) increases
fb through \(c\), then \(f\) has a {\bf local minimum} at \(c\).
fb <br><br>
fb If \(f'\) is positive on both sides near \(c\) or negative on boths
fb sides near \(c\), then \(f\) has no local extreme value at \(c\).

nn 4_9_one_local_extremum_implies_absolute
ln One Local Extremum Implies Absolute Extremum.
ln Suppose $f$ is continuous on an interval $I$ that contains
ln exactly one local extremum at $c$.
ln \par
ln If a local maximum occurs at $c$, then $f(c)$ is the absolute
ln maximum of $f$ on $I$.
ln \par
ln If a local minimum occurs at $c$, then $f(c)$ is the absolute
ln minimum of $f$ on $I$.
ff One Local Extremum Implies Absolute Extremum
fb Suppose \(f\) is continuous on an interval \(I\) that contains
fb exactly one local extremum at \(c\).
fb <br><br>
fb If a local maximum occurs at \(c\), then \(f(c)\) is the absolute
fb maximum of \(f\) on \(I\).
fb <br><br>
fb If a local minimum occurs at \(c\), then \(f(c)\) is the absolute
fb minimum of \(f\) on \(I\).

nn 4_10_test_for_concavity
ln Test for Concavity.
ln Suppose $f''$ exists on an open interval $I$.
ln \par
ln If $f'' > 0$ on $I$, then $f$ is concave up on $I$.
ln \par
ln If $f'' < 0$ on $I$, then $f$ is concave down on $I$.
ln \par
ln If c is a point of $I$ at which $f''$ changes sign at $c$
ln (from positive to negative, or vice versa), then $f$ has an
ln inflection point at $c$.
ff Test for Concavity
fb Suppose \(f''\) exists on an open interval \(I\).
fb <br><br>
fb If \(f'' > 0\) on \(I\), then \(f\) is concave up on \(I\).
fb <br><br>
fb If \(f'' < 0\) on \(I\), then \(f\) is concave down on \(I\).
fb <br><br>
fb If c is a point of \(I\) at which \(f''\) changes sign at \(c\)
fb (from positive to negative, or vice versa), then \(f\) has an
fb inflection point at \(c\).

nn 4_11_second_derivative_test_for_local
ln Second Derivative Test for Local Extrema.
ln Suppose $f''$ is continuous on an open interval containing $c$
ln with $f'(c) = 0$.
ln \par
ln If $f''(c) > 0$, then $f$ has a local minimum at $c$.
ln \par
ln If $f''(c) < 0$, then $f$ has a local maximum at $c$.
ln \par
ln If $f''(c) = 0$, then the test is nonconclusives; $f$
ln may have a local maximum, a local minimum, or neither at $c$.
ff Second Derivative Test for Local Extrema
fb Suppose \(f''\) is continuous on an open interval containing \(c\)
fb with \(f'(c) = 0\).
fb <br><br>
fb If \(f''(c) > 0\), then \(f\) has a local minimum at \(c\).
fb <br><br>
fb If \(f''(c) < 0\), then \(f\) has a local maximum at \(c\).
fb <br><br>
fb If \(f''(c) = 0\), then the test is nonconclusives; \(f\)
fb may have a local maximum, a local minimum, or neither at \(c\).

